-0026</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Academic research in the field of non-profit governance has shifted from an initial interest into the role of boards as a mechanism for managing uncertainties emanating from the external environment of organisations, to a focus on boards as a phenomenon of interest in and of themselves. Two predominant literatures have emerged as a result of this shift. The first examines board effectiveness. The second board composition.&lt;br />&lt;br />To date research on the composition of non-profit boards has focussed upon what could be referred to as ?supply-side factors? (ie, board size, demographic characteristics and the motivations of directors), as opposed to ?demand-side concerns? (i.e., board appraisal, succession plans and recruitment strategies). In order to address this imbalance, this research examined the non-executive director succession and recruitment practices of four major non-profit organisations - two higher education institutions and two social housing providers.&lt;br />&lt;br />Methodologically the study was qualitative and involved interviews with the CEOs, chairpersons, and non-executive directors of each of the four case study organisations. In addition to an examination of non-executive director recruitment and succession practices, the research also explored the:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>role of the board&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>the relationship between the CEO and the board&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>the motivations of non-executive directors.&lt;/li>

&lt;/ul></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-06-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>50563</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>8EB7A416-BEF9-435A-A585-5A0090AECBBC</gtr:id><gtr:title>Non-executive director succession and recruitment in NPOs : cases of social housing providers and universities</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/4b220ee974cf539d729ecf9842733f3c"><gtr:id>4b220ee974cf539d729ecf9842733f3c</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Simon Parris (Author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_122192660913c971e8</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>56394D54-1E7C-4964-AE5F-980CC6EEFC47</gtr:id><gtr:title>Board succession and recruitment strategies : the case of large charitable organisations in an era of fiscal constraint</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/4b220ee974cf539d729ecf9842733f3c"><gtr:id>4b220ee974cf539d729ecf9842733f3c</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Simon Parris (Author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_427870556713c96f54</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-073-27-0026</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier t